text:
every year there are opportunities to get #blackfriday and #cybermonday deals. in this year of #metoo, we recognize those who #givehope and #givehealing all year long.

today we would like you to meet ibilola ademodi! ibilola, who we affectionately call lola, is a hotline and medical advocate. she works as a mental health advocate at north county crisis stabilization and with elder folks at d'youville life and wellness community. lola has an m.s. in peace and conflict resolution from umass lowell. we are so proud to have her on our healingcorps team! 
here is what lola has to say about her experience with us. âœ¨â€my name is ibilola ademodi. my pronouns are she/her/hers. i am nigerian-american and i came to the united states to pursue a graduate degree, a privilege i do not take for granted. being given the opportunity to further my education to a graduate degree level is one that not many nigerians are [privileged] to have. a combination of lack of resources and little to no regard for sexual assault victims has led to the ineffectual approach to tackling sexual assault in nigerian communities. the fallout of victim blaming, cultural disregard and the little to no resources put into guarding survivors means that what survivors go through daily, especially women is completely dehumanizing.

hearing about chh and being given the opportunity to volunteer with them opened my eyes to the possible ways that i could not only utilize my skills but also give back to my community. the level of commitment, love, engagement and investment shown to me, has enabled me to not only volunteer but also serve as an intern for my final year practicum; it has been a rewarding and humbling experience. advocating for survivors every day is fulfilling for me. knowing that i have been able to advocate for a survivors through referrals, resources, counseling is an experience second to none." âœ¨

how will you give back this #givingtuesday?

text:
setiap 1 dari 3 wanita indonesia pernah mengalami kekerasan setidaknya sekali dalam seumur hidupnya, tanpa memandang tingkat pendidikan, status sosial atau usia mereka. korban sering terdiam karena mereka disalahkan dan kesaksian mereka diragukan.

untuk memperingati 16 hari aktivisme tahun ini melawan kekerasan berbasis gender, para influencer indonesia menyampaikan pesan yang kuat untuk mengakhiri kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan anak perempuan. dalam video tersebut, para influencer menekankan pentingnya bagi setiap orang untuk berbicara, berdiri dalam solidaritas dengan para penyintas dan pendukung dan bertindak untuk menghentikan normalisasi kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan anak perempuan.

kekerasan terhadap perempuan bukan hanya masalah perempuan, tetapi juga masalah setiap orang. sekarang saatnya untuk berbicara agar suara kita didengar. â—â—â— every 1 out of 3 indonesian women has experienced violence at least once in her lifetime, regardless of their level of education, social status or age. victims are often driven into silence because they are blamed and their testimonies are put in doubt.

to commemorate this year's 16 days of activism against gender based violence, indonesian influencers delivering a strong message to end violence against women and girls. in the video, the influencers emphasize the importance for everyone to speak out, stand in solidarity with survivors and advocates and act in order to stop normalizing violence against women and girls.

violence against women is not just a womenâ€™s issue, but also everyoneâ€™s issue. it is now time to speak up and for our voice to be heard.

#hearmetoo #16days #orangetheworld  #metoo #unwomen #genderequality

text:
in october 2017, raya sarkar, a law student, compiled a crowdsourced list of sexual harassers in academia, titled losha. although the intention of the list was more cautionary than to initiate institutional action, it encouraged women to speak and contribute their stories â€“ sometimes leading to investigations by the academic institutions.
in early 2017, a sexual harassment complaint was filed against an ashoka university professor, mitul baruah. the gender sensitisation committee against sexual harassment (gscash) in jawaharlal nehru university (jnu), where the complainant was a research scholar, found baruah guilty of manipulative consent and abuse of patriarchal power in the professional sphere. they declared him out of bounds from the university. despite the complainantâ€™s multiple requests for the action to be taken against the professor, the report of the concluded verdict was never given to her. they later reported that although baruah was guilty of sexual misconduct, he was not of harassment.
in october this year, the #metoo movement reached various indian campuses including the symbiosis centre for media and communication (scmc) in pune as several alumni accused their seniors and professors of sexual harassment. the alumni and students stated that the institution failed to take action against the accused faculty members, following which scmc authorities issued an apology on facebook assuring an investigation by their four-member internal complaints committee (icc). the director of scmc was sent on leave due to allegations of sexual harassment and abuse along with inaction towards reports of harassment by faculty members, two of whom were suspended. the administration also announced the introduction of their committee against sexual harassment (cash) cell.

recently on november 23, a female student from srm institute of science and technology was allegedly harassed by a male hostel staff in her hostel elevator where the man began masturbating in front of the girl.

in october 2017, raya sarkar, a law student, compiled a crowdsourced list of sexual harassers in academia, titled losha. although the intention of the list was more cautionary than to initiate institutional action, it encouraged women to speak and contribute their stories â€“ sometimes leading to investigations by the academic institutions.
in early 2017, a sexual harassment complaint was filed against an ashoka university professor, mitul baruah. the gender sensitisation committee against sexual harassment (gscash) in jawaharlal nehru university (jnu), where the complait was a research scholar, found baruah guilty of manipulative consent and abuse of patriarchal power in the professional sphere. they declared him out of bounds from the university. despite the complaitâ€™s multiple requests for the action to be taken against the professor, the report of the concluded verdict was never given to her. they later reported that although baruah was guilty of sexual misconduct, he was not of harassment.
in october this year, the #metoo movement reached various indian campuses including the symbiosis centre for media and communication (scmc) in pune as several alumni accused their seniors and professors of sexual harassment. the alumni and students stated that the institution failed to take action against the accused faculty members, following which scmc authorities issued an apology on facebook assuring an investigation by their four-member internal complaints committee (icc). the director of scmc was sent on leave due to allegations of sexual harassment and abuse along with inaction towards reports of harassment by faculty members, two of whom were suspended. the administration also announced the introduction of their committee against sexual harassment (cash) cell.

recently on november 23, a female student from srm institute of science and technology was allegedly harassed by a male hostel staff in her hostel elevator where the man began masturbating in front of the girl.
.
(continued in the comments)
.
graphics credits :- @lookingthrougharay

text:
introducing: to be vulnerably honest, a new youtube series from the artidote in collaboration with @under25official and @trijog. on this first episode, @harnidhk and i sit to have a vulnerably honest conversation about finding safety in a #metoo world.
â€¢
context: 
this past october, the #metoo movement exploded in india. coincidentally, i happened to be in the country running the artidote india tour when distraught and hurt-filled messages from some artidotees first made me aware of the news.
â€¢
the stories of sexual harassment and abuse against women sent shockwaves of ptsd through survivors across the country. it immediately became an unavoidable, collective conversation â€” and an extremely important one â€” on and off the internet. from my instagram inbox to some of the artidote moments that i hosted, anxious questions came in: where do i find safety in a world that feels so unsafe? how can i ever trust a man again? what if someone that i know is a sexual predator?
â€¢
i also had my own questions: what is my responsibility? as a man? as a friend?  how can i improve in being a safe space for others â€” both as a person and with the artidote?
â€¢
so when i had the opportunity to meet @harnidhk, poet and an overall powerhouse of a humane being, we couldn't help but to delve into that important conversation. her insights about safe spaces and boundaries were inspiring and empowering. her presence and words give a hopeful glimpse of seeing the breakthrough that tends to follow a breakdown.
â€¢
link to the full video is in the bio â¤ï¸

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
i felt hesitant making this post, but today this is very important to me. this post feels like a practice run for this afternoon. so, this is for me and for anyone else who needs to feel strong and safe in their own skin... despite all of the really negative emotions i have attached to these photos, i like them because they also remind me that i am bright and strong and beautiful and free, things that i need to be reminded of today as i face a dark space and person. on that note, to the man who took these photos, fuck you. i am a woman, but above all else i am a person, and you do not cause harm to people in the way that you caused harm to me. the things you have done feel unspeakable, but today i will suck up my fear and speak my truth. and i pray that it puts you in the place that you belong. if not, i have lost nothing. because you cannot take anything more from me. 
thank you to people in my life who continue to inspire and support me and make me feel strong. i love you.

#endviolenceagainstwomen #believeher #supportwomen #metoo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this #givingtuesday we are not asking you to simply donate. we are asking you to believe in a better world. one where women donâ€™t have to set their dignity on the nightstand to service a client and feed their kids. one where babies are not born and raised in brothels with their single mamma. one where hope exists. where pain and is met with jesus and new life springs forth. a world where women are believed in and educated. where abuse and rape are not dismissed or swept under the rug. a place where women are seen, heard and encouraged to pursue their dreams. 
we believe that world is possible. 
do you?

visit www.newlifecampaign.org and donate today!!! #endthecycle #webelieve #restoringdignity #empoweringwomem #haiti #metoo #timesup #redemption #changeherstory #worldmissions #inspire #equip #restore #fightfortheone #thenewlifecampaign

text:
if we can make jokes, we can make change. .
.
if we can't come together as a community to confront the blatant serial #sexualabuse of strangers - albeit famous ones - like @rkelly, we'll never be able to deal with the abuse that's happening in our own homes, churches and neighborhoods. .
.
it's time to stop making excuses for predatory behavior and blaming victims for what they've suffered, and start calling out abusers and making them face the consequences of their actions. .
.
while our call to #muterkelly may seem a passive and symbolic way to deal with a documented #pedophile and #childmolester, just having the conversation about why #rkelly should be shunned by our community goes a long way in helping everyone re-evaluate the abuse they turn a blind eye to in their own personal lives everyday. .
.
#endrapeculture #misogynoir #metoo #timesup

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

the picture on the left is me 12 years ago! then a victim now a victor! .
.
i am one of the few fortunate to be alive. some  left in a body bag and while many still suffer domestic violence because it remains widespread and is often considered "socially acceptableâ€ in nigeria. .
.
this is the reason family, friends and even some religious bodies do not see domestic violence as such a big deal. they believe itâ€™s the outcome of provocation and admonish victims never to annoy their abusers . but these abusers donâ€™t hit their bosses or colleagues who provoke them at work . they exercise restraints! .

domestic violence is not a result of provocation. iâ€™m writing this in capital letters and i hope it sinks in! violence and abuse is a tool used to enforce control, power and fear in a relationship or marriage and not a momentary expression of anger.
.
so stop judging victims by saying they were battered because of an imagined, perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like â€œwhat did you do that made him beat youâ€. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.
.
violence against women isn't cultural, its criminal. real men don't use violence! we must all join hands to eliminate violence against women and girls. our women must feel and know that they are not alone! .

there is no excuse for violence against women.  and yes, no excuse for violence against men either. 
don't justify it....don't judge them!
.
i am a victim turned victor ready to help other victims. join in , let's make a difference! .
.

the picture on the left is me 12 years ago! then a victim now a victor! .
.
i am one of the few fortunate to be alive. some  left in a body bag and while many still suffer domestic violence because it remains widespread and is often considered "socially acceptableâ€ in nigeria. .
.
this is the reason family, friends and even some religious bodies do not see domestic violence as such a big deal. they believe itâ€™s the outcome of provocation and admonish victims never to annoy their abusers . but these abusers donâ€™t hit their bosses or colleagues who provoke them at work . they exercise restraints! .

domestic violence is not a result of provocation. iâ€™m writing this in capital letters and i hope it sinks in! violence and abuse is a tool used to enforce control, power and fear in a relationship or marriage and not a momentary expression of anger.
.
so stop judging victims by saying they were battered because of an imagined, perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like â€œwhat did you do that made him beat youâ€. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.
.
violence against women isn't cultural, its criminal. real men don't use violence! we must all join hands to eliminate violence against women and girls. our women must feel and know that they are not alone! .

there is no excuse for violence against women.  and yes, no excuse for violence against men either. 
don't justify it....don't judge them!
.
i am a victim turned victor ready to help other victims. join in , let's make a difference! .
.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

a non

#repost @rachelmeyeryoga â€” hey yoga teachers: if you teach vinyasa, or lead teacher trainings, or ever ever ever teach the history of yoga, then you need to go listen to @jbrownyogaâ€™s new interview with karen rain, who was an early devotee of pattabhi jois, and whose refusal to be silent about the sexual assault she suffered under his tutelage is changing the face of ashtanga. thatâ€™s her there in the headstand at left, in this 1993 @yogaworks primary series video. next to her are richard freeman and tim miller, who went on to become ashtanga icons. why didnâ€™t she? because she was so traumatized by sexual assault at the hands of her â€œguruâ€ that she left her beloved practice completely, a troubling abusive pattern many fellow mysore practitioners witnessed and never called out.
.
the bottom line is that the vinyasa practice we know and love is largely a product of a serial sexual predator. gah. seriously. ğŸ¤¦ğŸ½â€â™€ï¸ so if you teach yoga history (especially to starry-eyed newbie teachers!) and leave this shit out, you are lying to your students. and doing a disservice to everyone who will ever study with them.
.
the shadow side of yoga is real. itâ€™s not pretty and itâ€™s not fun to talk about. but karen does a powerful job here of sharing her story, calling out privilege, and saying it like it is, even when itâ€™s uncomfortable. her voice shakes. listening, i feel her vulnerability and her bravery. and i recommit to telling the truth about the often-misogynistic history of yoga, even when it feels icky and uncomfortable.
.
we owe it to our students. be brave. do the hard work. they deserve the truth. itâ€™s more than just rainbows and unicorns. ğŸ¦„ğŸŒˆ
.

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text: today something remarkable happened â¤ï¸ something thatâ€™s significant in the final steps of my healing process.. a dear ig-friend of mine karen @keeping_moments_ sent me a pm. we donâ€™t know each other personally. she lives in the states and has family living here in the netherlands where i live. she asked me if i perhaps know the dutch village where her family now lives. as i started reading her message my breath stopped for a moment.. the village she was asking me about is the same village where i was abused as a child. out of all the villages and cities in holland she asked me about that particular place.. wow! goosebumps! as i got myself together i realized: this is no coincidence! after the abuse stopped i never went back to that village but lately i have been asking myself if i should/want to go back there one more time, just to pass by the house where it all took place. just to experience what that would do to me after all those years and now that iâ€™m an adult. and then, out of the blew, the question i have been quietly asking myself was answered by an ig-friend: yes, i need to go back there to close the cycle! and i will do so soon ğŸ™ we chatted a bit further and wondered if her family was now maybe living in the same house. she sent me photos of her familyâ€™s house but itâ€™s definitely not the same house. that would have been really freaky ğŸ˜… anyway, the point i wanna make here is that itâ€™s extremely important to openly communicate about our (often hidden) traumas, bad/sad experiences or anything we might be ashamed about! when we let it out we give other people the chance to respond. and they might surprise you in a positive way! besides that.. we all know the universe works in mysterious ways! ğŸ’« heartfelt thanks karen for reaching out to me today and bringing me the answer i was looking for! â¤ï¸ğŸ˜˜ ps. iâ€™m starting to think there might be more long posts coming up.. sorry ğŸ¤ª

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

.
the bottom line is that the vinyasa practice we know and love is largely a product of a serial sexual predator. gah. seriously. ğŸ¤¦ğŸ½â€â™€ï¸ so if you teach yoga history (especially to starry-eyed newbie teachers!) and leave this shit out, you are lying to your students. and doing a disservice to everyone who will ever study with them.

the shadow side of yoga is real. itâ€™s not pretty and itâ€™s not fun to talk about. but karen does a powerful job here of sharing her story, calling out privilege, and saying it like it is, even when itâ€™s uncomfortable. her voice shakes. listening, i feel her vulnerability and her bravery. and i recommit to telling the truth about the often-misogynistic history of yoga, even when it feels icky and uncomfortable.

text: sexual violence is pervasive and too secret a crime. the #metoo movement is just the beginning. we can affect social change in this area on an individual scale! -------------------------------------------------------------------------> exploring my sexual identities has been a messy process of undoing shame and increasing vulnerability. still, it has been a necessary aspect of learning to flourish. as a woman conditioned to prioritize others' pleasure, my explorations have taught me to see the grey areas of consent more clearly. in turn i have translated what i've learned to educating adults in my life as well as my son about what consent means to me. a major ally in this process is @thongria... thank you for your work!! #minorities #socialchange #notecard #endsexualviolence #profcarolhernandez #selfgrowth #shame #vulnerability

text:
a free maker event and closing party!!! ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ @uag_pitt is partnering with the university library system @pittlibraries @frickfineartslibrary on a maker event making change to take place during the closing celebration of the current exhibition this is not ideal on thursday, december 6 from 5-7pm. borrowing from major themes found within the exhibition, this event creates opportunities for participants to explore how works of art often reinforce conventional gender roles, while at the same time, in the face of #metoo, race and gender inequity, heterosexism and cisgender privilege, identify how we can challenge these myths. 
making change will offer a queer coloring and postcard writing station, a feminist button-making workshop, bookmaking demo, feminist bingo, and other art activities. the event is free and open to all, and will include pizza, sweet treats, and other refreshments. ğŸ•ğŸ•ğŸ• the exhibition this is not ideal has been curated by university of pittsburgh museum studies students. drawn from the university art gallery collection, the exhibition brings together works from the 17th century to the present that engage with shifting cultural norms of gender. this is not ideal also features new works by local contemporary artists @katieottwoodwork and @adammilner 
for more information, please contact the uag at uag@pitt.edu.

text: everyday grappling operations: on the unbearable richness of being a judoka latina and on my performative installation at ocma: in judo, one does not use brute force against oneâ€™s opponent but rather uses timing and an opponentâ€™s force to subdue them. after too many falls and practice, the judoka learns how to not get thrown off-balance easily by an opponent. it requires practice on multiple levels to learn the subtleties and depth of this practice. after a long hiatus, iâ€™m interested in re-engaging with this dynamic training and martial arts community as a way to access the kind of knowledge that allows one to build strength from a place of vulnerability and resilience in the face of hostile, uneven power relations. #everydaygrapplingoperations #ocma #judogirl #latinacontemporaryart #latinapower #intersectionalfeminisms #feministart #latinamericancontemporaryart #metoo #martialartspower #feministreadings #training

text:
this is my father. he turned 82 in august.  today, as i was searching for some of his poetry online to share with my young readers, a picture of me popped up right away - it was taken roughly 18 months ago, at the tail end of a long stretch of daily suicidal urges, and i look unrecognizable, so i'd rather erase any trace of that particular time. but once you become public, you don't get to hit delete, not really, so there we go: 
i came out to my mother a little after turning 39. dealing openly with past sexual abuse was a long time in the making, but i started talking only when keeping a secret was damaging me to the point of no return: it took a toll on my mental health, my professional life and my ability to maintain healthy personal relationships in ways i needed the better part of a quiet year to repair. 
telling my father - a smart, decent man, but very much the product of a different era - involved a fair amount of mutual  misunderstanding and a few fights during the stormier days of #metoo. he did the best he could when faced with what had happened to me when i was a kid, but he couldn't wrap his head around big stories involving women with public careers such as actors and musicians. i lost my temper, and so did he. a very tough conversation
along the lines of "where were *you* when i was being abused?" followed. it wasn't pretty, but it had to happen, and i got some answers. and so did he. 
today i decided to snap a picture of us together as a reminder we both got better but we still have a long way to go. but, we're still here. and we're starting to look like ourselves again. 
i love you dad. 
#abusesurvivor #family #suicide #mentalhealth #anxiety #depression #selfworth #comingout

telling my father - a sma, decent man, but very much the product of a different era - involved a fair amount of mutual  misunderstanding and a few fights during the stormier days of  he did the best he could when faced with what had happened to me when i was a kid, but he couldn't wrap his head around big stories involving women with public careers such as actors and musicians. i lost my temper, and so did he. a very tough conversation
along the lines of "where were *you* when i was being abused?" followed. it wasn't pretty, but it had to happen, and i got some answers. and so did he. 
today i decided to snap a picture of us together as a reminder we both got better but we still have a long way to go. but, we're still here. and we're staing to look like ourselves again. 
i love you dad.

from #25 november, the #internationaldayfortheeliminationofviolenceagainstwomen, to #10december, #humanrightsday, theÂ 16 days of activism against gender-based violence campaignÂ is a time to galvanize action to end violence against women and girls around the world. the international campaign originated from the first women's global leadership institute coordinated by the center for women's global leadership in 1991.

for far too long, impunity, silence and stigma have allowed violence against women to escalate to pandemic proportionsâ€”one in three women worldwide experience gender-based violence.

the time for change is here and now.

in recent years, the voices of survivors and activists, through campaigns such as #metoo, #timesup, #niunamenos, #notonemore, #balancetonporc and others, have reached a crescendo that cannot be silenced any more. advocates understand that while the names and contexts may differ across geographic locations, women and girls everywhere are experiencing extensive abuse and their stories need to be brought to light.

this is why the unite campaignâ€™s global advocacy theme this year is:Â #orangetheworld: #hearmetoo

under the theme orange the world: #hearmetoo, the unite partners are encouraged to host events with local, national, regional and global womenâ€™s movements, survivor advocates and women human rights defenders and create opportunities for dialogue between activists, policy-makers and the public. as in previous years, the colour orange will be a key theme unifying all activities, with buildings and landmarks lit and decorated in orange to bring global attention to the initiative.

join us!Â share your photos, messages and videos showing how you are participating in the campaign atÂ facebook.com/sayno.uniteÂ andÂ twitter.com/sayno_uniteÂ using #orangetheworld and #hearmetoo.Â for more information about orange the world: #hearmetoo,Â see this yearâ€™s concept note.

text:
addressing violence against women with disabilities. â€women with disability experience more severe violence more often than other women, are subjected to additional forms of violence because of their disability, and encounter more barriers when they try to protect themselves and seek justice. the social marginalisation and discrimination that women with disability experience can be compounded, for some, by reduced mobility, which limits capacity to escape violent situations. as a result, women with disability are at risk of the same forms of violence that other women face, but â€œalso experience forms of violence that are particular to their situation of social disadvantage, cultural devaluation and increased dependencyâ€. it is important to recognise that perpetrators of violence against women with disability may use specific forms of violence, as well as barriers faced by and specific to women with disability experiencing violence. to address violence against women with disability, an emphasis on more competent and responsive services is required, as well as consultation and coordination with organisations that are led by women with disability.â€ #16days #orangetheworld #hearmetoo #endvaw
#16days #intersectionality

text:
this year i have been through alot.
there have been ups and downs that i could easily say have been the some of the worst i've had to go through. it's been a hard year but i'm still here. i am able to learn, grow and smile through my struggles. i count my blessing each and everyday. so for that i just want to thank everyone for everything, especially to those that are still in my life.

#thankyou #life #greatful #mentalhealthawareness #survivor #metoo #lessonslearnedinlife #changes #changeforthebetter
name: Natalie Anderson

text:
when spring native simone biles speaks out about injustices in the world of usa gymnastics, she gets results. days after she blasted the idea of being forced to train once again at the karolyi ranch, the huntsville facility where she spent years perfecting her skills, usa gymnastics cut ties with martha and bela karolyi. during a press conference in august she criticized kerry perry, then the president of usa gymnastics, for moving too slowly to implement reforms. a few weeks later, perry was forced to resign. biles wasn't the only person who helped ultimately end usa gymnastics's status as the sport's national governing body, but itâ€™s hard to imagine an established institution falling so far so fast without her star power and moral stature at work. visit the link in our bio to read more from this installment of our december power issue. ğŸ“·: @joshhuskin

text:
empowerment isn't immunity.
.

been so fiercely focused on supporting, training, planning, writing, advocating... sometimes i actually forget how i got here. but a specific physical-contact trigger (not intended to cause harm, but the result is the result) caught me off guard this evening, and it's got every fight/flight mechanism tripped. .

the flood of chemicals, the heart knocking against the ribcage (is it trying to escape?), the shaking, the tears, and now the anger... with myself. .

for being so sensitive, still, after all these years. for letting the little stuff get to me today, so that i was primed for an extreme response. and yes, for directing the rage inward in the first place. .

these days happen, i suppose. to all of us. .

@thewordforthis

text:
part 2 #metoo (ha ha, pushing that share button was so fucking hard... i still feel the adrenaline rushing through my body...) there is no turning back now... it's hard to describe my emotional state of then. i can now compare it to the sort of trance one gets after a very serious accident... he kept on telling me how i reminded him of his first love and of all the pain he had been in when he lost her. he talked and talked and talked... i had been raised to be a good girl. speaking my mind and defending my rights and needs was not encouraged. i was raised to always see the others' perspective, to be kind and compassionate and look for the good in others. in my puberty years i thought i was becoming adult.. i was such a child and had no idea. 
my whole kind heart wanted to console the suffering i was seeing in that soul. in that moment something in me felt so sorry for him. for how lost he was and in pain. the need to help him overtook all the other emotions.
so i told him it's ok... i understand and i forgive him, as long as he swears not to do it again. (haha, i was such a child!) he was so pleased to hear that that he went on to hug me and to my utter disbelief touch me again... we then cycled back to the apartment where he and my aunt lived. it was a long cycle ride under a fiercely hot sun. i could taste the dust raising from the dirt road and feel it cacking my sweaty skin. my senses were coming back. the anger, the repulsion and the deep self loathing for allowing him to kiss me before getting on the bikes. 
i had had my lips sealed shut but nevertheless i consented to his lips touching mine. and for that i had no excuses. alowing him to touch me when he hugged me was inexcusable.  #raiseyourvibration #healthymindset #highvibetribe #youaremagic #spiritjunkie #youarepowerful #selfgrowth #positiveliving #thepowerofnow #peacefulmind #centred #peacewithin #liveinthenow #personalgrowth #spiritualgangsta #souljourney #loveandlight #lifelessons #spiritualgrowth

text:
vulnerability, healing, + forgiveness
â€¢â€¢
we close our hearts so often when weâ€™re suffering + in those moments we lose sight of who we really are. we sometimes donâ€™t even realize weâ€™re suffering because weâ€™re so focused on surviving each day.
â€¢
iâ€™ve debated about sharing this for a very long time + eventually decided fuck it, iâ€™m now strong enough mentally to speak on this + iâ€™m speaking my truth. however i still feel anxiety though my whole body just by posting this.
â€¢
my sole purpose in sharing my story is the hope that it will help let someone else suffering know that they arenâ€™t alone, i hear you, i believe you, your pain is valid, you do not/did not deserve this, i am here for you, and there is a light at the end of the long, dark tunnel.
â€¢
past traumas came up during my meditation a few days ago so iâ€™ve been very focused on dealing with them, healing + forgiveness: forgiving myself, forgiving others + forgiving the past.
â€¢
i thought i was being strong and self protecting by not telling anyone about this for a long time but i realized what keeps us safe + shows our strength is being vulnerable, speaking up, doing what we need to do to get through it so we can fight for ourselves + others.
â€¢
many many moons ago i was in a relationship where i thought i was in love with someone who verbally, emotionally, + eventually physically abused me + raped me. he was in a deep depression + i fell down the dark rabbit hole with him. the irony is i was taking a course on violence against women + girls at the time + kept convincing myself that i wasnâ€™t in an abusive relationship because it wasnâ€™t as bad as what i had been studying; i viewed it as minor abuse instead of severe + thought we were just going through a rough patch + that it would get better.
â€¢
i didnâ€™t know my self worth + i looked for others to love me instead of loving myself first.
â€¢
i had so many fears - fearful in dealing with it alone, getting out of it, potentially getting further abused by addressing it, being alone, losing friends over it. at the time i didnâ€™t know who to turn to in my inner circle who could understand + not judge me or him, so i opted to go it alone.
â€¢
(continued in comments)

text:
first of all, thereâ€™s a time & a place for powerful language. this is one of those times...
.
because babe, it is so important that you realize the power you hold to radically change your situation right now.
.
itâ€™s not your fault that shitty things happened to you. it hurts my heart to know of the pain youâ€™ve endured & the suffering youâ€™ve experienced due to some unfortunate & traumatic circumstances. you didnâ€™t deserve that, but it happened, & there is nothing we can do to change it.
.
but what you can do is change how you choose to view & use it to your advantage.
.
you are not your story babe. you are not those shitty things that happened to you or the traumatic ish someone said/did to you.
.
you are everything you decide to be as a result:
kind, loving, compassionate, forgiving, tenacious, assertive, intelligent, faithful, giving, grateful.
.
you have the power right now to choose how you want to write this next chapter. you went thru what you went thru because it didnâ€™t break you... it only made you stronger, wiser, & that much more determined to make something out of nothing.
.
so babe, what do you choose to act on today? do you commit to being more loving? can you commit to being more assertive? what about being a little more grateful?
.
acknowledge what happened.
accept your truth; that you get to decide how you view what happened & what you make of it.
act on it... asap.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
today i woke up feeling exhausted and overwhelmed with anxiety; my old-self would have fallen victim to my compulsive thoughts and paralyzed, and as a result get very little done.

instead of avoiding the uncomfortable i allowed myself to be curious, and let my anxiety move through me. it was definitely a struggle, i will not lie. but i do feel a sense of relief; and i am so proud of myself. and after posting this i will go have myself some chocolate.

the times when you are struggling are often when you need to practice self-compassion the most. think about the way you would talk to a friend and encourage them; have the same talk with yourself. in addition, engage in some self-care activities, such as taking a warm bath, reading a book youâ€™ve been wanting to read, cook your favorite meal or go and get a massage. be kind to yourself. donâ€™t beat yourself up for having anxious thoughts. and know your not alone.
.
.
.
#selfcare #selflove #motivation #struggles #anxiety #oldpatterns #faceyourfears #yournotalone #ptsd #metoo #ocd #anxious #courage #brave #mentalhealth #awareness #breannmcgregor

text:
i started our stories matter so victims of assault, abuse, and domestic violence can be heard. having been a victim, i felt it was important to do something to make change. and this project means so much to me. i also teamed up with licensed psychotherapist @cosmicchristine to help provide a safe place for people to come forward and open up. i am grateful for her support as well as her dedication to the cause.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
we are currently accepting submissions for the project. sharing your story not only can be therapeutic, but can help others with healing and break through the ignorance we see on the issue. and you can be anonymous if it makes you more comfortable. this collaborative journal will be real, raw, eye-opening, heartbreaking, and inspirational.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i am honored to read your story and include it in this special series of bravery and strength. you can learn more at ourstoriesmatter.info

text:
the best way to eradicate rape culture is to educate boys while they are young to respect girls and women as human beingsâ€”not objectsâ€” and to speak out against any behaviors that amount them to anything less. â€œwhat is rape culture and why is it a problem that boys benefit from and women suffer the consequences from?
.
rape culture is a thing. and boys and men are socialized to embrace it and celebrate it.
.
â€œrape culture is an environment that breeds characteristics which increase the likelihood that sexual harassment, assault, and rape will occur, through the justification that certain acts are not actually sexual offenses.â€- @sociologistray
.
acts such as catcalling, locker room guy talk about women, their bodies and sexual exploits, rape jokes, non-consensual pictures and videos, following/stalking, unsolicited flashing and dick pics, groping, cooing a feel, stealthing (covert condom removal), and victim blaming instead of realizing that about 95% of survivors are telling the truth.
.
collectively, these type of acts lead to the permission and acceptance of more heinous acts like drugging (including covert alcohol giving), sexual coercion, and rape.
.
what makes rape culture especially heinous at all levels is that whatâ€™s missing from the equation is womenâ€™s consent, their feelings, their humanity, and their own control over what happens to their bodies and mental and emotional health during and after these acts.â€ .
.
.
.
.

november 27th:

approximately every six days, a woman in canada is killed by her intimate partner. in the us, the number is almost 18x as much.

appalling statistics are used for more than just mere shock appeal. they serve as a constant reminder of the problems our societies still face and what we can do to help. at nisa helpline, we provide our callers with support ranging from marital disputes to domestic abuse. .

text: wait. donâ€™t give up.  as i watched the polls close and the reports come in i was shocked. democrats i thought for sure would win were losing. i became instantly upset and concerned. why be concerned about some congressional elections? because they make ultimate decisions that affect everyone, so who represents us is important. so i switched to a different tab and carried on with my work. a little later i checked and the result were still coming in, this time i felt relived and optimistic, more democratic candidates i was rooting for were in the lead. the change prompted me to look closer at the results. if a candidate was still behind it was by at most 10,000 votes. then i saw that only 13% of polling places had reported in. i now felt confident that the candidates with my support would win. 3 days later i have reflected on this. it reminded me that often things take time to turn out good. be patient and don't give up because it takes time for good to come. #metoo #believesurvivors #believewomen #politics #wait #dontgiveup #mystory #sumasopinion #democrats #weneedchange #vote #ivoted #ladygang #iamawoman #iam #notyourfault #ptsd #iwill #stronger #survivor #metoomeredith #ladylike

text:
disclaimer: 
i'm far from the mom who has it all together.

my smiles hide a lot of raw emotions iâ€™ve been keeping in and processing in the inside. the past 2 years of my life have been hard. really hard. making the conscious decision to start healing from a trauma from 22-23 years ago, becoming aware of myself, recognizing and dealing with triggers, dealing with my anxiety and depression & ptsd head on, becoming active again by running, starting/closing our company, trying different businesses to earn a side income to afford our bills + the extras, returning to â€œworkâ€ and being at home, being a mom to a school age child, financial uncertainty, elevated stress levels with health and wellbeing concerns of family & loved ones and the list goes on, and on... life is always going to place challenges and obstacles along our path that can make some days hard, really hard. countless days i've wanted to give up, but iâ€™ve learned to give myself grace in those moments, and try again the next day. i make the daily decision to move forward and live my best, my most true life.

iâ€™m was done being numb to the pain. as iâ€™ve  learned, when you numb the pain, you also numb the joy. sad to say, i was very productively living numb for far too long. i'm ready to focus on joy and bringing more of it into my life.

i have aligned myself with a company that focuses on mental health, reducing stress and anxiety and improving overall health and well being. 
time to focus on me, because i need it. 
i deserve it.
and i can't wait to help others too ğŸ˜‰

please know that i want to help. 
so if you're struggling, i'm here. 
if you need a safespace, i can offer one. 
if you need a shoulder, i have one. 
i've been there too... and still am. 
iâ€™m working on being a better me, each and every day. for myself, my family & greater community.

but one thing i know for certain, is how you handle your valleys teaches you lessons that mountaintops never could. ğŸ¢â¤ï¸ğŸ” much love, 
kelsie-ann
.

text: i got an assignment to write an essay for womenâ€™s roles this year about women in the media. i chose to write about the influence women have regarding sexual assault. it took me a long time to come to terms with my own assault and i still struggle to this day.  i think so many people feel like they will face consequences for speaking up or that people will not believe them.  i am thankful that there are women in the media sharing their experiences, that bravery of their own has opened up a lot of doors and given some people without a voice at least a sliver of the feeling of â€œi am not aloneâ€, including me. in this essay i specifically included the brave:@evanrachelwood @ladygaga and @reesewitherspoon  many others have come forward and spoke about their experiences and i am in no way am i trying to bring up triggers for anyone, but i wanted to share how unbelievably important these women are. #metoo #believewomen #metoomovement #womenempowerment #womensupportingwomen #jointhemovement

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

bothersome how the intimidation tactics and same rape culture abuser behavior is just fully being publically displayed throughout the country and communities. i feel violated, by a very dense city. i was violated. my life isn't in existence to be violated. i don't want to cuddle. i don't like you for the you you've displayed. it's fucked up, how being genuine and honest has, put me in another realm of silence. out here. pluto. have struggled to make friends due to speaking out. then being badgered so much made me not so willing to be friendly. now i meet new people from other places i feel text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text: mari beylerian was an armenian feminist who died in the armenian genocide. during her time in alexandria she taught at a local armenian school and between 1902-1903 she published the artemis armenian women's journal. beylerian accepted submissions not only from famous writers but from armenian women throughout the diaspora. she was especially interested in the role armenian women would play in the development of national identity. editorals authored by beylerian explored several women's rights themes, including motherhood. she believed women's education and employment were central to armenian national development. #istanbul #istanbulÃ¼niversitesi #turkiye #alexandria #rmenia #ermeniler #vangÃ¶lÃ¼ #armenian #feminist #susanbanthony #metoo #genocide #bibleverse #bible #armenianchurch djibin

text:
i bought this book for my kids. they were a bit confused about what it was talking about so i gave them an example. my example....
i went into minor details, enough to get them to understand not all people are good. kaia gave me a sweet hug. they asked me what the mans name was and i told them- cliff. they said â€œhaha, like falling off a cliff?â€ i said yep! i hope so! they asked if he was in jail- and i said hopefully or he is dead.
i never want my kids to not understand things about their bodies. i am a strong believer in being honest and open with them. books help guide these discussions. 
please talk to your children about all things important!! i share this not to get sympathy or pity but to heal, help those who feel alone or think nobody cares and for parents to talk to their kids. .
.
.
.

text:
pushing through the market square
so many mothers sighing
news had just come over
we had five years left to cry in
news guy wept and told us
earth was really dying
cried so much his face was wet
then i knew he was not lying

i heard telephones, opera house, favourite melodies
i saw boys, toys electric irons and t.v.'s
my brain hurt like a warehouse
it had no room to spare
i had to cram so many things
to store everything in there

and all the fat-skinny people
and all the tall-short people
and all the nobody people
and all the somebody people

i never thought i'd need so many people

a girl my age went off her head
hit some tiny children
if the black hadn't a-pulled her off
i think she would have killed them
a soldier with a broken arm
fixed his stare to the wheels of a cadillac
a cop knelt and kissed the feet of a priest
and a queer threw up at the sight of that

i think i saw you in an ice-cream parlour
drinking milk shakes cold and long
smiling and waving and looking so fine
don't think you knew you were in this song

and it was cold and it rained
so i felt like an actor
and i thought of ma
and i wanted to get back there
your face, your race
the way that you talk
i kiss you, you're beautiful
i want you to walk

we've got five years
stuck on my eyes
we've got five years
what a surprise
we've got five years
my brain hurts a lot
we've got five years
that's all we've got

david bowie

text:
pushing through the market square
so many mothers sighing
news had just come over
we had five years left to cry in
news guy wept and told us
earth was really dying
cried so much his face was wet
then i knew he was not lying

i heard telephones, opera house, favourite melodies
i saw boys, toys electric irons and t.v.'s
my brain hurt like a warehouse
it had no room to spare
i had to cram so many things
to store everything in there

and all the fat-skinny people
and all the tall-short people
and all the nobody people
and all the somebody people

i never thought i'd need so many people

a girl my age went off her head
hit some tiny children
if the black hadn't a-pulled her off
i think she would have killed them
a soldier with a broken arm
fixed his stare to the wheels of a cadillac
a cop knelt and kissed the feet of a priest
and a queer threw up at the sight of that

i think i saw you in an ice-cream parlour
drinking milk shakes cold and long
smiling and waving and looking so fine
don't think you knew you were in this song

and it was cold and it rained
so i felt like an actor
and i thought of ma
and i wanted to get back there
your face, your race
the way that you talk
i kiss you, you're beautiful
i want you to walk

we've got five years
stuck on my eyes
we've got five years
what a surprise
we've got five years
my brain hurts a lot
we've got five years
that's all we've got

david bowie

text:
i mingled among hollywood recently hearing stories of how women have fought through obstacles to greatness within the industry. they welcomed me into this new era of female film makers and catalysts for change. their stories would now be heard. 
soon after, i saw my artist rise in the tejano music scene. a beacon of hope for latinas. a breath of fresh air. she would have my full support. 
i then walked the grounds of mission san jose in san antonio, tx feeling the energy of both the spaniards and the native indians and imagined their life much different than mine. much simpler.. yet much harder. how difficult it must have been for both to merge into what we now call texans. 
they were at the beginning of it all. they had laid the groundwork for me to walk the path i do now.

i came home to realize that there was still much left to do in south texas for women, for texas, and for our voice to be heard. 
i canâ€™t change the past. but i can make history.

text:
pushing through the market square
so many mothers sighing
news had just come over
we had five years left to cry in
news guy wept and told us
earth was really dying
cried so much his face was wet
then i knew he was not lying

i heard telephones, opera house, favourite melodies
i saw boys, toys electric irons and t.v.'s
my brain hurt like a warehouse
it had no room to spare
i had to cram so many things
to store everything in there

and all the fat-skinny people
and all the tall-short people
and all the nobody people
and all the somebody people

i never thought i'd need so many people

a girl my age went off her head
hit some tiny children
if the black hadn't a-pulled her off
i think she would have killed them
a soldier with a broken arm
fixed his stare to the wheels of a cadillac
a cop knelt and kissed the feet of a priest
and a queer threw up at the sight of that

i think i saw you in an ice-cream parlour
drinking milk shakes cold and long
smiling and waving and looking so fine
don't think you knew you were in this song

and it was cold and it rained
so i felt like an actor
and i thought of ma
and i wanted to get back there
your face, your race
the way that you talk
i kiss you, you're beautiful
i want you to walk

we've got five years
stuck on my eyes
we've got five years
what a surprise
we've got five years
my brain hurts a lot
we've got five years
that's all we've got

david bowie

text:
anaunguruma ni wimbo wa hiphop kutoka kwa wasanii wa kubuni selementally pamoja na recho.wimbo huu unatoa picha halisi ya maisha ya msichana wa kitanzania na changamoto anazokutana nazo katika masuala ya kielimu, kijamii na kifamilia.

video hii inaonyesha changamoto,ugumu na vizingiti anavyokutana navyo msichana ambapo wavulana hawakutani na changamoto hizo sababu tu ya jinsia zao.video hii inaonyesha nguvu ya msichana wa kitanzania (kiafrika) inaonyesha uvumilivu ,kujituma na kutokukata tamaa ili kutimiza malengo yao. pia inaonyesha kuwa wasichana wana sauti kubwa tena inayounguruma kama jamii itawapa nafasi kuwasikiliza basi wasichana watafanya mambo makubwa na kuinua familia zao na jamii nzima.

lakini cha muhimu zaidi video hii inaonyesha kuwa wavulana/wanaume wanatakiwa kusikiliza na kuzipaza sauti za wanawake.wanaume wana nafasi katika kuleta usawa wa kijinsia,mfano kuna kampeni inafanyika ulimwengu mzima inaitwa #metoo.kwenye wimbo huu story inasimuliwa na selementally ambaye ni mwanaume ila anapaza sauti ya mwanamke na changamoto zake hii ni kuonyesha kuwa wanaume wanatakiwa kuwasaidia wanawake katika kutatua changamoto zao ,wanatakiwa kusikiliza muungurumo wao.hii ni muhimu hasa kwa nchi zinazoendelea ambapo wasichana /wanawake wamekuwa wakiogopa kuripoti matatizo yao ya kijinsia hivyo kutokusikika na ulimwengu.hivyo kwa kufanya kazi pamoja (wanaume na wanawake ) tutaweza kutengeneza mazingira mazuri kwa wasichana wa kitanzania ,afrika na ulimwengu mzima

wimbo huu umeandikwa na kufanywa na vijana kutoka kubuni centre ,selementally, recho ,boazi na pie shot.mtayarishaji wa mdundo ni gachi b kutoka blackdot music.kupitia kubuni music tunataka kuleta muziki wenye maana na ujumbe mzuri kwa jamii.muziki utakafanya vijana wa kitanzia na ulimwengu mzima kufanya maamuzi sahihi juu ya maisha yao.

olive branch for children ni shirika ambalo linafanya kazi tanzania kwa miaka kumi sasa na miradi yake kama kubuni center imeendelea kutoa nafasi kwa vijana kama kuwapatia nafasi za masomo nje ya nchi nafasi za kujifunza kazi na uzoefu wa kazi lakini pia vijana kuonesha vipaji vyao.tunaamini watu wote bila kuwabagua kijinsia au kivyovyote  wanahitaji kupewa nafasi.

text:
a woman and her three daughters. after dozens of appeals to the police went unanswered, this woman separated from her abusive ex-husband. still, she cannot count on local law enforcement to protect her rights. 
despite a 2012 law which raised the maximum prison sentence for â€œfemicide,â€ the killing of a woman or girl on account of her gender, argentina is still struggling against widespread gender-based violence. thankfully, a grassroots, women-led movement known as ni una menos (not one [woman] less) has arisen in argentina, and is working to empower women and defend their human rights. in this series, karl mancini (@karlitomancini) shares some of his work on the inspiring women of ni una menos and their fight for justice. to learn more about both mancini's work and ni una menos, please follow the link in our bio.

text:
enough.  this is the testimony and siren song of my own bladed femininity and the potent identities of others turned to ends of visceral enlightenment.  enough silencing of those subjected to the abrupt assault on potential that constitutes sexual violence.  enough quelling of truth, discussion, and debate for the sake of the "delicate equilibrium" of a societal ecosystem already dangerously unbalanced.  i am fiercely proud to announce the upcoming publication of my poetry in the rumpus' enough series, a collection of work by female and non-binary writers commenting on sexual assault and rape culture.  keep an eye out for my poem, "pulp oracle," but take some time to examine the existing body of work here: https://therumpus.net/sections/blogs/enough/
#poetry #publication #protest #enough #metoo #timesup #female #empowerment #whistleblower #breakthesilence #art #protestart #kungfu #jian #sword

text:
we met with the amazing @natashanoel001 during the @joshtalkslive & @unwomen #hearmetoo conference at india habitat centre. check out our live video to hear her speak with us on what it means to be a global citizen today ! 
natasha exemplifies everything it means to be a global citizen to us, she overcame many challenges in her life to be a role model to many youth in the country by speaking out about her past trauma and is now a yoga star, a motivational speaker, a photographer, a blogger, a dancer and a huge social media sensation!

thank you for being such a rockstar, more power to you @natashanoel001 !

text:
women only stay away seminar.
maandag 7 januari tussen 19.00 en 21.30u is het zover.

krav maga eindhoven organiseert een empowerment event voor alle dames die zich willen kunnen verdedigen en hun mentale weerbaarheid willen vergroten.

tijdens dit 2.5 uur durende zelfverdediging cursus leer en oefen je niet alleen super effectieve zelfverdedigingstechnieken, maar krijg je ook een inkijkje in mentale en verbale vaardigheden die je kunt in zetten om voor jezelf op te komen

een absolute aanrader als jij als vrouw volledig in je kracht wilt staan! weg met die weerloosheid. kom op met die innerlijke kracht.

slechts â‚¬25,- per persoon!

meld je snel aan via: info@kravmagaeindhoven.nl
er zijn nog enkele plekken beschikbaar!
#stayaway
#zelfverdediging 
#selfdefense #kravmagaholland #kravmaganoordbrabant #kravmagaeindhoven 
#women #empowerment
#takecontrole 
#metoo

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

text:
"my mama is my biggest inspiration. she is a researcher and academic who has worked in various ngos, governments and international organizations over the past two decades.

however, before all that, she was a victim of sexual violence and forced marriage. she was forced to marry my dad because her mom didn't value her individuality, just because she is a woman.she struggled to break boundaries, and to claim her individuality.

every time my parents fought, my mama always locked me inside my room, put headphones over my ears and played enya or classical music so that i could not hear what was happening. as i grew up, i knew stories about what happened and i hated my father for it.

mama tried her best to protect me. when i was three and a half years old my mama divorced and left him. afterwards mama worked hard to finish her degree, start her career in ngos then continue her study in finland and germany.

years passed by. mama went through two more divorces. those men come and go, running around leaving scars. mama basically raised two children alone, and taught us the values of justice, non-violence, and forgiveness.

i once asked her; â€œwhy did you have me in this world? you never wanted to be married.â€ she said, â€œi wouldnâ€™t be able to be this strong if it wasnâ€™t for you.â€ from what my mama taught me, nothing is stronger than forgiveness and understanding. so i eventually forgave my father.
now i'm trying to understand him more as a person. 
my mama is the reason why i do everything i do. she made me believe that there are still good in this world. from her experience, i also learned that the issue of gender-based violence isn't only about women. this is about human decency." ------- margianta surahman, founder and ed of emancipate indonesia, @oneyoungworld ambassador and co-cordinater or heforshe indonesia shares his story. 
#togetherweroar #hearmetoo #16daysofactivism #16days #heforshe #metoo

every time my parents fought, my mama always locked me inside my room, put headphones over my ears and played enya or classical music so that i could not hear what was happening. as i grew up, i knew stories about what happened and i hated my father for it.

mama tried her best to protect me. when i was three and a half years old my mama divorced and left him. afterwards mama worked hard to finish her degree, sta her career in ngos then continue her study in finland and germany.

years passed by. mama went through two more divorces. those men come and go, running around leaving scars. mama basically raised two children alone, and taught us the values of justice, non-violence, and forgiveness.

i once asked her; â€œwhy did you have me in this world? you never wanted to be married.â€ she said, â€œi wouldnâ€™t be able to be this strong if it wasnâ€™t for you.â€ from what my mama taught me, nothing is stronger than forgiveness and understanding. so i eventually forgave my father.
now i am trying to understand him more as a person. 
my mama is the reason why i do everything i do. she made me believe that there are still good in this world. from her experience, i also learned that the issue of gender-based violence is not only about women. this is about human decency." ------- margianta surahman, founder and ed of emancipate indonesia,  ambassador and co-cordinater or heforshe indonesia shares his story.

text:
boys will not be boys
+ if you carry around all the emotional weight, because you feel like you're not allowed to express your feelings as a guy.
+ if you want to take care of kids but are refused to be accepted as the main caretaker.
+ if you reject so called 'strong leaders' who talk about raping, abusing and denigrating women.
+ if you do not want to talk about women in a misogynistic way.
+if you're the one 'seeing an issue where there is none'.
+ if you want to be the man you would like to be. -- the effect? --
society locks you up in a massive cage of normativity and 'stay in your place-ism'. this is an even stronger cage for women, never underestimate the disparity. 
it's time for us men to reject the fact that we must always be 'the leader' and 'strong', 'emotionless', 'reserved' because society wants us to.

it is time for us to get a hold of our identity and stop societal toxicity from pushing us into corners.

i refuse to be a toxic masculine man.
----
