text:
so people are asking whoâ€™s the person behind this account.
.
well here i am, smashing the patriarchy since 1982 and still kicking itğŸ’ª
.
but ofc iâ€™m not doing this alone (b/c that would be like banging my head against the wall) - i got my squad, my co-founders, my friends and all of you backing me up.
.
iâ€™ve been a hard rock and metal fan since i was about 10 years old, and from early on i was told that was weird. i was weird. i wasnâ€™t cool enough to hang with the guys, not girly enough to hang with the girls. my whole life people have told me i talk too much. i speak my opinion too much. i am too much. and thatâ€™s right; iâ€™ve never been capable fitting in or keeping my mouth shut when i see or hear things that go completely against my core values; that every person is entitled to a voice and human rights. and as i see it, thereâ€™s no way iâ€™m just gonna sit back and watch all this systematic and structural oppression and abuse of women around the world and do nothing.
.
the music industry, including rock and metal, is mirroring the rest of society: women are marginalized, oppressed, reduced, abused and silenced - in a very man dominated sphere on, behind and off stage.
.
me and co-founder sofia - both active metal and rock music reporters for several years - had enough, and dear darkness was born 2,5 years ago. before the #metoo movement hit hard. iâ€™m now running this account and #metaltoo and even tho iâ€™ve had my moments where i just want to give up (b/c itâ€™s a struggle and the widespread misogyny is real), i remind myself i have to keep going. for me, for my 7 year old daughter, for my sisters and all the women out there.
.
feminism is for everyone, the entire society will benefit from equality, but i need you - yes everyone of you - to spread the word. to support. to share our message. to influence others. to make demands. to take action. all over the world.
.
if thereâ€™s anything youâ€™d like to help with - ig posts, ig movies, tips, local actions and what not - all ideas are appreciated - please drop me a pm and weâ€™ll take it from there.
.
got any questions, youâ€™re very welcome to ask and iâ€™d be happy to respond.
.
keep fighting!ğŸ‘Š
.
love,
frida

text_retweet: ğŸ’œ af3irm sf/bay area participates in 16 days of activism to amplify the voices of women of color impacted by gender-based violence. ğŸ’œ today and all days we say, â€œstop! that was harassment!â€ because we know that our silence as transnational women of color will not protect us. ğŸ’œ whether at a coffee shop or restaurant, working on stuff or just hanging out, by myself or with friends, i have experienced sexual harassment, unwanted advancements, and inappropriate touching by male strangers who unabashedly presumed their persistence and entitlement to my body, time, and energy as a filipina woman in a public space. sometimes, i have felt too petrified to speak. other times, and more so, i acknowledged my power, strength, and fury as a woman by loudly demonstrating that i did not tolerate their male entitlement and shouted at them to leave me alone and to go away. so that everybody around could see and hear what was happening. so that everybody around could understand that a womanâ€™s body, time, and energy are not for others. so that everybody around could understand that women will not be silenced or coerced into perpetuating our own oppression. so that we, as women, can be at home in the world and just chill. ğŸ’œ we reclaim our space and affirm ourselves by taking up as much space as possible in a culture that tries to stifle our voices and make us feel small. ğŸ’œ join us and repost this message and #af3irmyourself by saying no to sexual violence. we encourage you to share your story. #16daysofactivism #16days #metoo #hearmetoo #endviolenceagainstwomen #endviolenceagainstwomenandgirls #diasporareflections #woc #feminism #transnationalfeminism #af3irm #af3irmsf @af3irm @af3irmsf

text:
meet kalkidan, age 14, grade 7. while i meet her during my hiking at ankober, she was studying her social science outdoor on a sunny day and herding her family's cattle.
i'm amazed by her dedication. she is polite, sociable, and an outstanding student (stood 2nd from her class last year). she told me she wants to be a doctor when she grows up.

text:
i absolutely adore what i do...
_
what comes up time and time again though... is how many of us are doing what we think we should be doing...
_
not what we want to be doing.
_
it doesn't have to be that complicated.
_
it doesn't have to have all the drama attached.
_
it can just be what it is... but we get caught up in the rules, in the systems of how we should be living and how we should be feeling and ....
_
we make decisions or avoid them based on that.
_
so ask yourself some simple questions to break it down:-
_
1. if no one had an opinion about it, how would you feel?
_
2. if no ones feelings could get hurt, what would you do?
_
3. is the fear of failure/success, stopping you from taking action?
_
4. if you stopped being 'practical' about it, what would you decide?
_
5. will you survive if it doesn't work out?
_
have some fun with it... its your life after all ğŸ˜˜

_
not what we want to be doing.
_
it does not have to be that complicated.
_
it does not have to have all the drama attached.
_
it can just be what it is... but we get caught up in the rules, in the systems of how we should be living and how we should be feeling and ....
_
we make decisions or avoid them based on that.
_
so ask yourself some simple questions to break it down:-
_
1. if no one had an opinion about it, how would you feel?
_
2. if no ones feelings could get hu, what would you do?
_
3. is the fear of failure/success, stopping you from taking action?
_
4. if you stopped being 'practical' about it, what would you decide?
_
5. will you survive if it does not work out?
_
have some fun with it... its your life after all ğŸ˜˜

text:
s/he seems genuine, and that is what makes it so difficult to believe they are cold-blooded planners! in fact, there are times we serve a purpose in their lives so much so that they really do treat us well or with kindness and "love"... but it's not the kind of love that lasts throughout the ages. it's not the kind of love that makes dreams come true. it's a fake love, one that they most likely don't feel in the same way we do. it's that we are satisfying a need for them. 
once we no longer serve their needs, they will and can turn on us. in fact, they may slip along the way and turn on us, and we get hurt. how could s/he say something so mean and hurtful? that's because they have no moral boundaries.

in the end, if we love them to the end, they will eventually discard us in the most awful and brutal way. they do not care. the countless loving things that were said at an earlier time in our relationship? those things don't matter because they were not said with genuine love. 
this is why the end can be so brutal. they can be super dangerous. they can be callous. or... they may leave without so much as an unkind word. there are all levels of narcissism. but what matters most to you and me is that we learn to see them for what they are: cold and careless. and after we are done crying over the loss of what we thought we had, we best learn from this, let go and don't let ourselves get sucked back into their toxic world or anyone else's.

text:
pyjamas are forgiving by @twinklerkhanna â€œthe mind knows it deserves better; it is the heart that forgets.â€ good (not great), funny (not hilarious), filmy (not too much though), good one-time read. 
the basic plot of this book is based on a woman in her 40s who is divorced and rekindles her chemistry with her ex-husband at a health retreat. while i love how twinkle khanna has a unique tone in her voice, this one didn't impress much. the setting is unique and the characters grow on you soon especially anshu. it all still seemed like a bollywood movie going on (which i am sure will soon release). there has always been a strong tone and uniqueness to her stories but this one didn't make the cut. maybe she has set the expectations too high? a gay couple and a feminism/#metoo angle was a good touch but seemed forced to give relevance. all in all, it is a good one-time read. looking forward to her next novel.

text:
@regran_ed from @narcissist_free -  s/he seems genuine, and that is what makes it so difficult to believe they are cold-blooded planners! in fact, there are times we serve a purpose in their lives so much so that they really do treat us well or with kindness and "love"... but it's not the kind of love that lasts throughout the ages. it's not the kind of love that makes dreams come true. it's a fake love, one that they most likely don't feel in the same way we do. it's that we are satisfying a need for them. 
once we no longer serve their needs, they will and can turn on us. in fact, they may slip along the way and turn on us, and we get hurt. how could s/he say something so mean and hurtful? that's because they have no moral boundaries.

in the end, if we love them to the end, they will eventually discard us in the most awful and brutal way. they do not care. the countless loving things that were said at an earlier time in our relationship? those things don't matter because they were not said with genuine love. 
this is why the end can be so brutal. they can be super dangerous. they can be callous. or... they may leave without so much as an unkind word. there are all levels of narcissism. but what matters most to you and me is that we learn to see them for what they are: cold and careless. and after we are done crying over the loss of what we thought we had, we best learn from this, let go and don't let ourselves get sucked back into their toxic world or anyone else's.

text:
"we have evolved hundreds and thousands of years as women by adapting to our environment in ways that would ensure our survival.  we know that when it comes to survival skills these are often the most difficult to modify or change due to the survival weight they carry. we have learned from our motherâ€™s and grandmotherâ€™s how they responded as women based on the choices that were available for them. how that translates for women today, is that we need to cultivate new skills, new ways of deeply listening for what action, movement or statement any given situation may call for. resilience is a practice of deeply listening and allowing ourselves to be guided by what is most authentic within us. at la maida we gather to learn and explore how we can cultivate awareness and skills to greet our world with wisdom, compassion and action that supports our continued individual and collective growth." - alexa altman, phd
ğŸ’—
join us tonight for resilient women: building resilience in a difficult world, with dr. altman, anjali deva and julie fernandez, 7-9pm. 
__________

text:
(poem below) i created this art journal page a while ago but when i stumbled upon it this morning, this poem was born. i love how art is forever giving. for those who love with complex ptsd, depression, anxiety, those who are abuse survivors, i know how hard it can be to make peace with yourselves. i know that the pain can feel so big and that the inner child can feel really demanding. i know for me it's taken a lot of hard work to be able to begin to embrace my inner child. this poem was a turning point for me and i hope that this poem provides some comfort.ğŸ¤—
.
.
.
i am ready to make amends. 
to let go of the shame.
to begin again.
to know my heart.
to see my soul.
to nurture my broken back to whole.
ğŸŒ±
i am ready to make amends.
to forgive myself.
to reach out to friends.
to nourish my body 
to fuel my mind
leaving no part of me behind. ğŸŒ±
i am ready to make amends. 
to trust my gut.
to live again.
to honor my needs.
to pause, to pray.
to practice gratitude every day.
ğŸŒ±
this morning i chose to make amends.
with someone special,
my very first friend.
i'm sorry i judged you 
and just couldn't see
how brave you've been for you and me.
ğŸŒ±
you've loved me unconditionally.
with all my flaws and idiosyncrasies. 
you've been by my side right from the start.
yet i convinced myself we had grown apart.
you've always known we would see it through 
but life got hard and i ran from you.
ğŸŒ±
please know i'm here now
and i'm here to stay. 
to celebrate us, to grow, and to play.
i see all of you. and i know you see me.
together, as one, we can finally be
the eccentric friend.
the imperfect mom,
the poem, the painting
the breathtaking song.
ğŸŒ±
we are now free to be who we choose
to live out our dreams
to heal all our wounds
to feel our feels
to fall our falls 
to rest.
to rise.
to answer the call. ğŸ’–
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

despite a 2012 law which raised the maximum prison sentence for â€œfemicide,â€ the killing of a woman or girl on account of her gender, argentina is still struggling against widespread gender-based violence. thankfully, a grassroots, women-led movement known as ni una menos (not one [woman] less) has arisen in argentina, and is working to empower women and defend their human rights. in this series, karl mancini (@karlitomancini) shares some of his work on the inspiring women of ni una menos and their fight for justice. to learn more about both mancini's work and ni una menos, please follow the link in our bio.

text:
andrew moisey gained unfettered access to an american fraternity for the purposes of documenting their daily lives. even more damning, though, when set against the atavism depicted via photos and various other material, are the lists of prominent ex-greeks: senators, presidents, bishops (whose list faces a photo of two frat pledges, clad only in boxers, grasping their protruding testicles in such a way that they resemble octopus heads). moisey has some concerns his work will have some seeing him as a â€œfrat broâ€ but we insist you read our review of his book â€˜the american fraternityâ€™ to gain unprecedented insight into the organizations that shape young men, and can bring much harm to them and young women.

text:
on your journey to healing, another question to consider is "have i asked for what i need?"
often times we feel like others aren't responding to us the way we need them to, be it emotionally or physically. however, we are not always clear about what we want or need from others. be clear about what you need from the people in your life. whether it is a hug, an explanation, an apology, space, an opportunity to vent, their participation in your counseling sessions, or some other act of support, you need to be clear. remember, you are a survivor! #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text: i can't believe it. after all the sexual abuse, harassment and rape happening to me i still have not learned how to stand up for myself. here's the story of today: i invited the father of big child's classmate for coffee. we met multiple times, are friends with the family, walk to school together a lot. and he hits on me. advertises himself as good lover and touches me in all the inappropriate places and ways, before i manage to make my point clear: stop it or leave my house, right now. and he even started a staredown, to find out if i was actually meaning it or just wanted to be a more interesting prey. why the f* can i, after all my history, still not look out better for myself? i had the whole smiling nervously and stepping aside thing going, watching myself and asking what the hell i am doing here, not saying no. i am so conditioned something inside even said "one more time will actually not do any more damage to your soul anymore". and now i drown in guilt and shame for a thing that's not my fault to begin with. i should not be in this situation to begin with!!! shit like this happens all the time, to all of us. how can we make all the male a*holes go extinct? proposals in the comments, i am in. #metoo

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still, today, right now.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

a non

text:
"i was raped.â€â €
i uttered these words as i fell forward, head in my hands, shaking on my therapistâ€™s couch ğŸ›‹ it took me a long to time to utter these words, let alone accept them. the word rape feels dirty. like we are damaged, like there is something wrong with us that we would allow this to happen. â €
â €
for so long i justified the situation to myself... i was the one that invited him to the party, i was the one that was so drunk and high. if i hadnâ€™t let myself get so wasted this wouldnâ€™t have happened. is this true? probably. and that doesnâ€™t mean that itâ€™s my fault. we can take responsibility for our part in a situation and not be to blame. blame and responsibility are two very different things that are often collapsed in our culture and minds.â €
â €
when working with clients, i often talk about this concept. itâ€™s a tricky line to walk, ğŸ›£ one that must be done carefully and diligently. not everyone is ready to have this conversation. those of us that are not in the acceptance stage are not ready to have this conversation. people who are actively in a traumatizing situation are also not in the space to have this conversation.  you cannot safety process a situation you are currently being traumatized by. â €
â €
however, for my friends that are ready, i encourage you to look at this with an open mind. itâ€™s actually empowering to take responsibility for your part in a situation. to be clear, for many of us, the only responsibility we may have is that we allowed it to keep us small and control our lives for so long. this is also not to say that we were wrong because of this. we did what we needed to do to survive. and thank god for that. it isnâ€™t her fault, but with knowledge now it becomes her responsibility to heal. now taking that on, thatâ€™s real power ğŸ’¥â €
â €
this leads me to one of my favorite #quotes, ğŸ™Œ â€œyour wound is probably not your fault, but your healing is your responsibility.â€ - denice frohman â €
â €
whether we have trauma or not, taking responsibility for healing our wounds is an empowering context to live our lives. checkout the link in my bio for my recent blog post and let me know what you think! #whyididntreport #metoo #endrapeculture #timesup

text:
-supporting a survivor of homicide-

there are many things we can do to support a survivor of homicide.  sometimes survivors feel that their loved one is forgotten because no one speaks of them.  in reality, the supportive person doesnâ€™t know what to say about their loss, so they avoid the subject altogether. weâ€™re afraid we will say the wrong thing and the survivor will cry or be distressed. speaking the lost loved oneâ€™s name and remembering them in good memory can be incredibly healing. 
how can we support a survivor of homicde? 
1. say, "i am so sorry that this happened to you and (name the survivor)." when appropriate, you can add â€˜and your familyâ€™. 2. say the victimâ€™s name in conversation. talk about special or happy memories you have of the victim. 
3. allow them to talk about their loved one.
4. sit silently with the victim. just be there.
5. let them cry. there is no such thing as too many tears. *november 20th until december 20th is survivors of homicide awareness month. we will be highlighting survivors of homicide periodically throughout the month as a part of access' homicide and violent crimes program*

text:
rip harry leslie smith. anti-austerity campaigner, wwii veteran and refugee rights activist. 
he was born into the north of england at a time of great economic downturn, and lost his sister to tb whilst still a young boy, having not been able to pay for sufficient healthcare. as a young man, he answered the call to fight the nazis, and he served in the royal air force during the second world war.

returning to britain, he saw not only a broken country, but an opportunity to reform- clement attlee. deeply affected by the loss of his sister, he threw himself behind the idea of the nhs, and became one of its greatest advocate up until the day he died, being famously known as the â€œworldâ€™s oldest rebel.â€ following the refugee crisis in the 2010s, he became a refugee rights activist, truly touched by the plight of those who had nothing- something he saw as similar to the acceptance of refugees before and during the second world war.

a fierce opponent of the austerity imposed upon britain by the conservative government, he fought for the rights of the voiceless, and especially fought for the life and soul of his beloved nhs. 
he goes down in history as a man with an unblemished record- a hero, a fighter, and a true champion of the voiceless.

text:
@regran_ed from @abuse_survivor -  @regran_ed from @mercyiaspire -  the picture on the left is me 12 years ago! then a victim now a victor! .
.
i am one of the few fortunate to be alive. some  left in a body bag and while many still suffer domestic violence because it remains widespread and is often considered "socially acceptableâ€ in nigeria. .
.
this is the reason family, friends and even some religious bodies do not see domestic violence as such a big deal. they believe itâ€™s the outcome of provocation and admonish victims never to annoy their abusers . but these abusers donâ€™t hit their bosses or colleagues who provoke them at work . they exercise restraints! .

domestic violence is not a result of provocation. iâ€™m writing this in capital letters and i hope it sinks in! violence and abuse is a tool used to enforce control, power and fear in a relationship or marriage and not a momentary expression of anger.
.
so stop judging victims by saying they were battered because of an imagined, perceived or rumored wrong or asking them annoying questions like â€œwhat did you do that made him beat youâ€. questions like these are unintelligent and insensitive.
.
violence against women isn't cultural, its criminal. real men don't use violence! we must all join hands to eliminate violence against women and girls. our women must feel and know that they are not alone! .

there is no excuse for violence against women.  and yes, no excuse for violence against men either. 
don't justify it....don't judge them!
.
i am a victim turned victor ready to help other victims. join in , let's make a difference! .
.

text: the #metoo movement in india is working miracles but at the same time the lashback it's gotten is enormous but divided. the lashback that's saying that the movement currently is attacking innocent men is stupid however the other part that's saying that false accusations will begin increasing in the future if the #metoo movement starts majorly advocating guilty until proven innocent and continues to stick to ruining careers without evidence and giving priority to women to an unreasonable extent is pretty rational. but again, whenever someone says the movement is stupid and i dig further into their opinion, it's usually just anti-feminist because it's a stupid conservative dude or it's someone who is not a fan of any products of current feminism because of its toxicity and irrationality and extreme liberalness in first world countries. the latter which i completely understand since not everyone has the time to keep following and updating themselves with developments of a movement especially after seeing the bad fruits of the tree.

text:
quiet as a mouse ii
30â€x40â€

the good olâ€™ boys club just wants women to be quiet, donâ€™t speak up, donâ€™t have a voice, donâ€™t have independent thought and definitely donâ€™t be in a power position. they want to keep you tied up and quiet. 
speak up. unite. demand equality. 
do not be silent! roar. 
arguably a top 5 indelible image and first cartoon character of our childhood years. 
minnie will never be the same. 
a mere part of a larger series of artworks that were to be, and are, my commentary on where it seems our country, society and culture is today compared to when i was a child. 
the crux of the series is based on childhood cartoons and characters that i had grown up with and that represent my childhood. now, these characters are distorted into something that will never, at least unlikely, be the same again. they used to be sharp, clean lines and brightly colored.... now they are rough, dirty, twisted and in black and white. 
i hope you like it. it is also a bit of therapy for me realizing a dealing with the state of our country right now.
